node.text:
What an extremely informative chat regarding mindfulness and anxiety.
Speaking with professor/scientist and author @drshaunashapiro and Therapist @kimberleyquinlan we speak about the definition of mindfulness, how to approach mindfulness with compassion, how best to practice mindfulness and the scientific evidence behind mindfulness for anxiety

node.text: Dean speaks with @doc_amen about the impacts of pressure and fame on our mental health. How important it is to prioritise your mental health and how proud we all are of the steps @simonebiles has taken to put her mental health first.

node.title: The weight of gold @simonebiles discussion with @doc_amen

node.title: Anxiety recovery! Recovery room series 2 episode 1

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by DLC Anxiety Worldwide 🌍 on September 03, 2021 tagging @dlclive, and @allyse_has_anxiety. May be an image of text that says 'What You See Vs. What I Feel (High Functioning Anxiety Edition) @ALLYSE_HAS_ANXIETY'.

node.text:
Doctors do not recognize high functioning anxiety as a distinct anxiety condition, and there is a distinct lack of research in the area. However, some people with anxiety symptoms describe themselves as being high functioning. By this, they typically mean that they manage to function well in their day-to-day lives.
@allyse_has_anxiety (art)
@dlclive
-
-
-
-#hfa #highfunctioninganxiety #anxious #ansiedadegeneralizada

node.text: @wearemindlabs I gotta admit it when I was in the middle of a panic disorder I was praying for recovery to be a straight line process. But it wasn’t, there were bumps in the road and set backs along the way. But I got there, I went from 4 panic attacks a day to zero in 3 years. If I can do it you can too. Keep going ❤️❤️

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by DLC Anxiety Worldwide 🌍 on September 01, 2021 tagging @kimberleyquinlan. May be an image of text that says 'Types of Compulsions CBTschool.com @kimberleyquinlan'.
Photo by DLC Anxiety Worldwide 🌍 on September 01, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Compulsions can be physical or mental. CBTschool.com @kimberleyquinlan'.

Photo by DLC Anxiety Worldwide 🌍 on September 01, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Compulsions are anything that is done to immediately remove the anxiety, doubt, physical discomfort, or uncertainty that comes from obsessions. CBTschool.com @kimberleyquinlan'.

Photo by DLC Anxiety Worldwide 🌍 on September 01, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Physical compulsions might include: doing something a specific number of times (washing your hands, taking a sip of water), picking at your skin, doing things "just right" (stacking the dishes, folding the laundry CBTschool.com @kimberleyquinlan'.

Photo by DLC Anxiety Worldwide 🌍 on September 01, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Avoidant Compulsions might include: Avoiding any person, object, substance, thought, or or place that triggers the obsession CBTschool.com @kimberleyquinlan'.

Photo by DLC Anxiety Worldwide 🌍 on September 01, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Mental compulsions might include: rumination, mental "reviewing" of past events, checking (your attraction level, how your body feels, what emotions you are feeling) CBTschool.com @kimberleyquinlan'.

Photo by DLC Anxiety Worldwide 🌍 on September 01, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Reassurance compulsions include: Googling asking loved ones questions, frequently visiting doctors or professionals related to your obsession, etc. CBTschool.com @kimberleyquinlan'.

Photo by DLC Anxiety Worldwide 🌍 on September 01, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'The only way to break the obsessive-compulsive cycle is to practice uncertainty and discomfort. CBTschool.com @kimberleyquinlan'.

Photo by DLC Anxiety Worldwide 🌍 on September 01, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'When you have the urge to do a compulsion, you can thank it for trying to keep you safe, but let it know that's not necessary. You're not in danger. CBTschool.com @kimberleyquinlan'.

Photo by DLC Anxiety Worldwide 🌍 on September 01, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says '3. Pectoral Pain When we have pain in the chest muscles near the heart and we misinterpret this as a heart problem. @anxiełyjosh'.

Photo by DLC Anxiety Worldwide 🌍 on September 01, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says '4. Chest Flutters With indigestion we can sometimes feel a flutter at the top of our sternum. This can be misinterpreted as our heart beating out of of rhythm. @anxietyjosh'.

node.text:
@malminder.gill.therapy❤️❤️
Repeat after me THOUGHTS ARE NOT FACTS. Just because we think something doesn’t make it any more true, yet when we are anxious we mistakenly assume that because we have had a response to the thought, that the thought is true. ❌ This is not the case! Use this space to share any anxious thoughts that have been consuming your mind lately below ⬇️⬇️⬇️

May be an image of text that says 'Finding a cure for my anxiety & insomnia "It sounds within two weeks of supplementing with these dietitian recommended nutrients, my anxiety had reduced dramatically. I was sleeping through the night... was amazed, especially given nothing else had worked yet. Maybe this dietitian was on to something..." @DanMurraySerter'.

Photo by DLC Anxiety Worldwide 🌍 on August 29, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Vitamins Ð vitamins play a beneficial role in reducing anxiety and improving your mood. A study published in the Journal of Functional Foods found that people who ate Ð vitamin rich foods saw significant improvements in their anxiety and stress scores. Vitamin B12 is especially powerful for managingyour mood. @DanMurraySerter'.

Photo by DLC Anxiety Worldwide 🌍 on August 29, 2021. May be an image of text that says '#2 Vitamin c This antioxidant plays a vital role in maintaining homeostasis (i.e. balance) in your central nervous system. Studies have shown that "vitamin c deficiency is widely associated with stress-related diseases" and notes that taking a vitamin c supplement may improve your mood and reduce anxiety. Vitamin c can also help your body to better manage its cortisol levels. @DanMurraySerter'.

Photo by DLC Anxiety Worldwide 🌍 on August 29, 2021. May be an image of text that says '#3Vitamin D Approximately 40% of Europeans don't get enough vitamin D. There' a correlation between low vitamin D levels and higher rates of anxiety and other mood disorders. One study even found that taking a vitamin D supplement helped improve symptoms of depression. @DanMurraySerter'.

Photo by DLC Anxiety Worldwide 🌍 on August 29, 2021. May be an image of text that says '#4 Zinc Studies have shown that symptoms of depression and low mood can be improved by zinc supplementation for some people. Zinc contributes to healthy brain function, with an important role in the production of serotonin, the key hormone that stabilizes our mood, feelings of well-being, and happiness, and other neurotransmitters. @DanMurraySerter'.

Photo by DLC Anxiety Worldwide 🌍 on August 29, 2021. May be an image of text that says '#5 Omega 3 DHA & ΕΡΑ High stress levels deplete the brain's reserves of omega 3, as the body releases omega 3 into the bloodstream to provide extra energy as the fight or flight response is triggered. Links have been found between omega 3 supplementation and lowered stress levels, marked reductions in anxiety levels and inflammation in the brain. @DanMurraySerter'.

Photo by DLC Anxiety Worldwide 🌍 on August 29, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'HEIGHTS The Smart Supplement Seeing the role that supplements played in my braincare, it seemed natural to help others do the same. Iteamed up with co-founder Joel Freeman, Neuroscientist Dr Tara Swart, and dietitian Sophie Medlin, to develop the Heights Smart Supplement. Combining the 20 essential healthy fats, antioxidants, vitamins, and minerals your brain and body need to thrive @DanMurraySerter'.
